#Use kubectl commands to create, scale, and manage Kubernetes resources like pods and deployments.


✅ Step 0 – Start Kubernetes (Minikube)


minikube start
kubectl get nodes



kubectl create deployment myapp --image=nginx:latest

kubectl scale deployment myapp --replicas=3
kubectl get pods

kubectl scale deployment myapp --replicas=1
kubectl get pods

kubectl expose deployment myapp --port=80 --type=NodePort





Get pod name
kubectl get pods
Describe pod
kubectl describe pod <pod-name>
View logs
kubectl logs <pod-name>


🧹 Cleanup


kubectl delete deployment myapp
kubectl delete service myapp


📄 Step 4 – Using YAML


Create file: deployment.yaml


apiVersion: apps/v1
kind: Deployment
metadata:
  name: myapp
spec:
  replicas: 2
  selector:
    matchLabels:
      app: myapp
  template:
    metadata:
      labels:
        app: myapp
    spec:
      containers:
      - name: myapp
        image: nginx:latest
        ports:
        - containerPort: 80



Apply YAML

kubectl apply -f deployment.yaml

✔ Check everything

kubectl get all

Example output:

deployment.apps/myapp
pod/myapp-xxxx Running
service/myapp






